In this problem, you are given a doubly linked list and asked to sort it using merge sort.

The given doubly linked list node class has the following structure:

    `public class Node {
        int val;
        Node prev;
        Node next;
    }

` 

You should write a function to merge two sorted linked lists into one. Note that you can only access the linked list using the `head` node.

The `merge` function should return the `head` of the merged linked list. 


This is the buggy `merge` implementation:

```python
def merge(self, l1, l2):
    if l1 is None: return l2
    if l2 is None: return l1
    if l1.val < l2.val:
        l1.next = self.merge(l1.next, l2)
        return l1
    else:
        l2.next = self.merge(l1, l2.next)
        return l2
```

This implementation incorrectly merges the linked lists. The `merge` function is supposed to return the `head` of the merged linked list.

